  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "These are the memoirs of Nehemiah son of Hacaliah.In late autumn,
        in the month of Kislev, in the twentieth year of King Artaxerxes\u2019 reign,[COMMENT[0]]
        I was at the fortress of Susa. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'In the month of Kislev of the twentieth year. '
        - ft: 'A number of dates in the book of Nehemiah can be cross-checked with
            dates in surviving Persian records and related accurately to our modern
            calendar. This month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred within
            the months of November and December 446 '
          body: 'twentieth year '
        - ft: probably refers to the reign of King Artaxerxes I; compare 2:1; 5:14.
          body: 
    - title: "Nehemiah\u2019s Concern for Jerusalem"
      content: 'Hanani, one of my brothers, came to visit me with some other men
        who had just arrived from Judah. I asked them about the Jews who had returned
        there from captivity and about how things were going in Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They said to me, \u201CThings are not going well for those who returned
        to the province of Judah. They are in great trouble and disgrace. The wall
        of Jerusalem has been torn down, and the gates have been destroyed by fire.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I heard this, I sat down and wept. In fact, for days I mourned,
        fasted, and prayed to the God of heaven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I said,\n\t\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, God of heaven,
        the great and awesome God who keeps his covenant of unfailing love with those
        who love him and obey his commands, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'listen to my prayer! Look down and see me praying night and day for
        your people Israel. I confess that we have sinned against you. Yes, even
        my own family and I have sinned! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We have sinned terribly by not obeying the commands, decrees, and
        regulations that you gave us through your servant Moses.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease remember what you told your servant Moses: \u2018If
        you are unfaithful to me, I will scatter you among the nations. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if you return to me and obey my commands and live by them, then
        even if you are exiled to the ends of the earth,[COMMENT[0]] I will bring
        you back to the place I have chosen for my name to be honored.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: of the heavens.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe people you rescued by your great power and strong hand
        are your servants. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "O Lord, please hear my prayer! Listen to the prayers of those of
        us who delight in honoring you. Please grant me success today by making the
        king favorable to me.[COMMENT[0]] Put it into his heart to be kind to me.\u201D\n\tIn
        those days I was the king\u2019s cup-bearer."
      comments:
      - number: '1:11 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: today in the sight of this man.
  - verses:
    - title: Nehemiah Goes to Jerusalem
      content: "Early the following spring, in the month of Nisan,[COMMENT[0]] during
        the twentieth year of King Artaxerxes\u2019 reign, I was serving the king
        his wine. I had never before appeared sad in his presence. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'In the month of Nisan. '
        - ft: 'This month of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar occurred within the
            months of April and May 445 '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "So the king asked me, \u201CWhy are you looking so sad? You don\u2019t
        look sick to me. You must be deeply troubled.\u201D\n\tThen I was terrified, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "but I replied, \u201CLong live the king! How can I not be sad? For
        the city where my ancestors are buried is in ruins, and the gates have been
        destroyed by fire.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king asked, \u201CWell, how can I help you?\u201D\n\tWith a prayer
        to the God of heaven, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I replied, \u201CIf it please the king, and if you are pleased with
        me, your servant, send me to Judah to rebuild the city where my ancestors
        are buried.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king, with the queen sitting beside him, asked, \u201CHow long
        will you be gone? When will you return?\u201D After I told him how long I
        would be gone, the king agreed to my request.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I also said to the king, \u201CIf it please the king, let me have
        letters addressed to the governors of the province west of the Euphrates
        River,[COMMENT[0]] instructing them to let me travel safely through their
        territories on my way to Judah. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'the province beyond the river; '
        - ft: also in 2:9.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "And please give me a letter addressed to Asaph, the manager of the
        king\u2019s forest, instructing him to give me timber. I will need it to
        make beams for the gates of the Temple fortress, for the city walls, and
        for a house for myself.\u201D And the king granted these requests, because
        the gracious hand of God was on me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When I came to the governors of the province west of the Euphrates
        River, I delivered the king\u2019s letters to them. The king, I should add,
        had sent along army officers and horsemen[COMMENT[0]] to protect me. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: charioteers.
    - title: 
      content: 'But when Sanballat the Horonite and Tobiah the Ammonite official
        heard of my arrival, they were very displeased that someone had come to help
        the people of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Nehemiah Inspects Jerusalem\u2019s Wall"
      content: 'So I arrived in Jerusalem. Three days later, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I slipped out during the night, taking only a few others with me.
        I had not told anyone about the plans God had put in my heart for Jerusalem.
        We took no pack animals with us except the donkey I was riding. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After dark I went out through the Valley Gate, past the Jackal\u2019s
        Well,[COMMENT[0]] and over to the Dung Gate to inspect the broken walls and
        burned gates. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: "Serpent\u2019s Well."
    - title: 
      content: "Then I went to the Fountain Gate and to the King\u2019s Pool, but
        my donkey couldn\u2019t get through the rubble. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So, though it was still dark, I went up the Kidron Valley[COMMENT[0]]
        instead, inspecting the wall before I turned back and entered again at the
        Valley Gate.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the valley.
    - title: 
      content: "The city officials did not know I had been out there or what I was
        doing, for I had not yet said anything to anyone about my plans. I had not
        yet spoken to the Jewish leaders\u2014the priests, the nobles, the officials,
        or anyone else in the administration. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now I said to them, \u201CYou know very well what trouble we
        are in. Jerusalem lies in ruins, and its gates have been destroyed by fire.
        Let us rebuild the wall of Jerusalem and end this disgrace!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I told them about how the gracious hand of God had been on me,
        and about my conversation with the king.\n\tThey replied at once, \u201CYes,
        let\u2019s rebuild the wall!\u201D So they began the good work.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when Sanballat, Tobiah, and Geshem the Arab heard of our plan,
        they scoffed contemptuously. \u201CWhat are you doing? Are you rebelling
        against the king?\u201D they asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I replied, \u201CThe God of heaven will help us succeed. We, his
        servants, will start rebuilding this wall. But you have no share, legal right,
        or historic claim in Jerusalem.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Rebuilding the Wall of Jerusalem
      content: 'Then Eliashib the high priest and the other priests started to rebuild
        at the Sheep Gate. They dedicated it and set up its doors, building the wall
        as far as the Tower of the Hundred, which they dedicated, and the Tower of
        Hananel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'People from the town of Jericho worked next to them, and beyond them
        was Zaccur son of Imri.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Fish Gate was built by the sons of Hassenaah. They laid the beams,
        set up its doors, and installed its bolts and bars. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meremoth son of Uriah and grandson of Hakkoz repaired the next section
        of wall. Beside him were Meshullam son of Berekiah and grandson of Meshezabel,
        and then Zadok son of Baana. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next were the people from Tekoa, though their leaders refused to
        work with the construction supervisors.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Old City Gate[COMMENT[0]] was repaired by Joiada son of Paseah
        and Meshullam son of Besodeiah. They laid the beams, set up its doors, and
        installed its bolts and bars. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'The Mishneh Gate, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: The Jeshanah Gate.
    - title: 
      content: 'Next to them were Melatiah from Gibeon, Jadon from Meronoth, people
        from Gibeon, and people from Mizpah, the headquarters of the governor of
        the province west of the Euphrates River.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the province beyond the river.
    - title: 
      content: 'Next was Uzziel son of Harhaiah, a goldsmith by trade, who also worked
        on the wall. Beyond him was Hananiah, a manufacturer of perfumes. They left
        out a section of Jerusalem as they built the Broad Wall.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: They fortified Jerusalem up to the Broad Wall.
    - title: 
      content: 'Rephaiah son of Hur, the leader of half the district of Jerusalem,
        was next to them on the wall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next Jedaiah son of Harumaph repaired the wall across from his own
        house, and next to him was Hattush son of Hashabneiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then came Malkijah son of Harim and Hasshub son of Pahath-moab, who
        repaired another section of the wall and the Tower of the Ovens. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Shallum son of Hallohesh and his daughters repaired the next section.
        He was the leader of the other half of the district of Jerusalem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Valley Gate was repaired by the people from Zanoah, led by Hanun.
        They set up its doors and installed its bolts and bars. They also repaired
        the 1,500 feet[COMMENT[0]] of wall to the Dung Gate.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '1,000 cubits '
        - ft: '[460 meters].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'The Dung Gate was repaired by Malkijah son of Recab, the leader of
        the Beth-hakkerem district. He rebuilt it, set up its doors, and installed
        its bolts and bars.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Fountain Gate was repaired by Shallum[COMMENT[0]] son of Col-hozeh,
        the leader of the Mizpah district. He rebuilt it, roofed it, set up its doors,
        and installed its bolts and bars. Then he repaired the wall of the pool of
        Siloam[COMMENT[1]] near the king\u2019s garden, and he rebuilt the wall as
        far as the stairs that descend from the City of David. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:15a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Syriac version; Hebrew reads '
          body: Shallun.
      - number: '3:15b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'pool of Shelah, '
        - ft: another name for the pool of Siloam.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Next to him was Nehemiah son of Azbuk, the leader of half the district
        of Beth-zur. He rebuilt the wall from a place across from the tombs of David\u2019s
        family as far as the water reservoir and the House of the Warriors.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next to him, repairs were made by a group of Levites working under
        the supervision of Rehum son of Bani. Then came Hashabiah, the leader of
        half the district of Keilah, who supervised the building of the wall on behalf
        of his own district. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next down the line were his countrymen led by Binnui[COMMENT[0]]
        son of Henadad, the leader of the other half of the district of Keilah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:18 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in a few Hebrew manuscripts, some Greek manuscripts, and Syriac
            version (see also 3:24; 10:9); most Hebrew manuscripts read '
          body: Bavvai.
    - title: 
      content: 'Next to them, Ezer son of Jeshua, the leader of Mizpah, repaired
        another section of wall across from the ascent to the armory near the angle
        in the wall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next to him was Baruch son of Zabbai, who zealously repaired an additional
        section from the angle to the door of the house of Eliashib the high priest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meremoth son of Uriah and grandson of Hakkoz rebuilt another section
        of the wall extending from the door of Eliashib\u2019s house to the end of
        the house.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next repairs were made by the priests from the surrounding region. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After them, Benjamin and Hasshub repaired the section across from
        their house, and Azariah son of Maaseiah and grandson of Ananiah repaired
        the section across from his house. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Next was Binnui son of Henadad, who rebuilt another section of the
        wall from Azariah\u2019s house to the angle and the corner. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Palal son of Uzai carried on the work from a point opposite the angle
        and the tower that projects up from the king\u2019s upper house beside the
        court of the guard. Next to him were Pedaiah son of Parosh, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'with the Temple servants living on the hill of Ophel, who repaired
        the wall as far as a point across from the Water Gate to the east and the
        projecting tower. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then came the people of Tekoa, who repaired another section across
        from the great projecting tower and over to the wall of Ophel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Above the Horse Gate, the priests repaired the wall. Each one repaired
        the section immediately across from his own house. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next Zadok son of Immer also rebuilt the wall across from his own
        house, and beyond him was Shemaiah son of Shecaniah, the gatekeeper of the
        East Gate. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next Hananiah son of Shelemiah and Hanun, the sixth son of Zalaph,
        repaired another section, while Meshullam son of Berekiah rebuilt the wall
        across from where he lived. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Malkijah, one of the goldsmiths, repaired the wall as far as the
        housing for the Temple servants and merchants, across from the Inspection
        Gate. Then he continued as far as the upper room at the corner. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: The other goldsmiths and merchants repaired the wall from that corner
        to the Sheep Gate.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Enemies Oppose the Rebuilding
      content: '  [COMMENT[1]]Sanballat was very angry when he learned that we were
        rebuilding the wall. He flew into a rage and mocked the Jews, '
      comments:
      - number: 
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
      - number: '4:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
        - ft: Verses 4:1-6 are numbered 3:33-38 in Hebrew text.
          body: 
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "saying in front of his friends and the Samarian army officers, \u201CWhat
        does this bunch of poor, feeble Jews think they\u2019re doing? Do they think
        they can build the wall in a single day by just offering a few sacrifices?[COMMENT[0]]
        Do they actually think they can make something of stones from a rubbish heap\u2014and
        charred ones at that?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Tobiah the Ammonite, who was standing beside him, remarked, \u201CThat
        stone wall would collapse if even a fox walked along the top of it!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I prayed, \u201CHear us, our God, for we are being mocked. May
        their scoffing fall back on their own heads, and may they themselves become
        captives in a foreign land! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Do not ignore their guilt. Do not blot out their sins, for they have
        provoked you to anger here in front of[COMMENT[0]] the builders.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:5 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: for they have thrown insults in the face of.
    - title: 
      content: 'At last the wall was completed to half its height around the entire
        city, for the people had worked with enthusiasm.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '  [COMMENT[1]]But when Sanballat and Tobiah and the Arabs, Ammonites,
        and Ashdodites heard that the work was going ahead and that the gaps in the
        wall of Jerusalem were being repaired, they were furious. '
      comments:
      - number: 
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
      - number: '4:7 '
        contents:
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
        - ft: Verses 4:7-23 are numbered 4:1-17 in Hebrew text.
          body: 
        - ft: '  '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'They all made plans to come and fight against Jerusalem and throw
        us into confusion. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But we prayed to our God and guarded the city day and night to protect
        ourselves.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people of Judah began to complain, \u201CThe workers are
        getting tired, and there is so much rubble to be moved. We will never be
        able to build the wall by ourselves.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, our enemies were saying, \u201CBefore they know what\u2019s
        happening, we will swoop down on them and kill them and end their work.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Jews who lived near the enemy came and told us again and again,
        \u201CThey will come from all directions and attack us!\u201D[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'So I placed armed guards behind the lowest parts of the wall in the
        exposed areas. I stationed the people to stand guard by families, armed with
        swords, spears, and bows.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then as I looked over the situation, I called together the nobles
        and the rest of the people and said to them, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid of
        the enemy! Remember the Lord, who is great and glorious, and fight for your
        brothers, your sons, your daughters, your wives, and your homes!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When our enemies heard that we knew of their plans and that God had
        frustrated them, we all returned to our work on the wall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But from then on, only half my men worked while the other half stood
        guard with spears, shields, bows, and coats of mail. The leaders stationed
        themselves behind the people of Judah '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'who were building the wall. The laborers carried on their work with
        one hand supporting their load and one hand holding a weapon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the builders had a sword belted to their side. The trumpeter
        stayed with me to sound the alarm.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I explained to the nobles and officials and all the people,
        \u201CThe work is very spread out, and we are widely separated from each
        other along the wall. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When you hear the blast of the trumpet, rush to wherever it is sounding.
        Then our God will fight for us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'We worked early and late, from sunrise to sunset. And half the men
        were always on guard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I also told everyone living outside the walls to stay in Jerusalem.
        That way they and their servants could help with guard duty at night and
        work during the day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "During this time, none of us\u2014not I, nor my relatives, nor my
        servants, nor the guards who were with me\u2014ever took off our clothes.
        We carried our weapons with us at all times, even when we went for water.[COMMENT[0]]"
      comments:
      - number: '4:23 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'Each carried his weapon in his right hand. '
        - ft: 'Hebrew reads '
          body: 'Each his weapon the water. '
        - ft: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
          body: 
  - verses:
    - title: Nehemiah Defends the Oppressed
      content: 'About this time some of the men and their wives raised a cry of protest
        against their fellow Jews. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They were saying, \u201CWe have such large families. We need more
        food to survive.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Others said, \u201CWe have mortgaged our fields, vineyards, and homes
        to get food during the famine.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And others said, \u201CWe have had to borrow money on our fields
        and vineyards to pay our taxes. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We belong to the same family as those who are wealthy, and our children
        are just like theirs. Yet we must sell our children into slavery just to
        get enough money to live. We have already sold some of our daughters, and
        we are helpless to do anything about it, for our fields and vineyards are
        already mortgaged to others.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I heard their complaints, I was very angry. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After thinking it over, I spoke out against these nobles and officials.
        I told them, \u201CYou are hurting your own relatives by charging interest
        when they borrow money!\u201D Then I called a public meeting to deal with
        the problem.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At the meeting I said to them, \u201CWe are doing all we can to redeem
        our Jewish relatives who have had to sell themselves to pagan foreigners,
        but you are selling them back into slavery again. How often must we redeem
        them?\u201D And they had nothing to say in their defense.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I pressed further, \u201CWhat you are doing is not right! Should
        you not walk in the fear of our God in order to avoid being mocked by enemy
        nations? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I myself, as well as my brothers and my workers, have been lending
        the people money and grain, but now let us stop this business of charging
        interest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must restore their fields, vineyards, olive groves, and homes
        to them this very day. And repay the interest you charged when you lent them
        money, grain, new wine, and olive oil.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe will give back everything and demand nothing
        more from the people. We will do as you say.\u201D Then I called the priests
        and made the nobles and officials swear to do what they had promised.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I shook out the folds of my robe and said, \u201CIf you fail to keep
        your promise, may God shake you like this from your homes and from your property!\u201D\n\tThe
        whole assembly responded, \u201CAmen,\u201D and they praised the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.
        And the people did as they had promised.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the entire twelve years that I was governor of Judah\u2014from
        the twentieth year to the thirty-second year of the reign of King Artaxerxes[COMMENT[0]]\u2014neither
        I nor my officials drew on our official food allowance. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: "That is, 445\u2013433 "
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'The former governors, in contrast, had laid heavy burdens on the
        people, demanding a daily ration of food and wine, besides forty pieces[COMMENT[0]]
        of silver. Even their assistants took advantage of the people. But because
        I feared God, I did not act that way.  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '40 shekels '
        - ft: '[1 pound or 456 grams].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'I also devoted myself to working on the wall and refused to acquire
        any land. And I required all my servants to spend time working on the wall. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I asked for nothing, even though I regularly fed 150 Jewish officials
        at my table, besides all the visitors from other lands! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The provisions I paid for each day included one ox, six choice sheep
        or goats, and a large number of poultry. And every ten days we needed a large
        supply of all kinds of wine. Yet I refused to claim the governor\u2019s food
        allowance because the people already carried a heavy burden.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Remember, O my God, all that I have done for these people, and bless
        me for it.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Continued Opposition to Rebuilding
      content: "Sanballat, Tobiah, Geshem the Arab, and the rest of our enemies found
        out that I had finished rebuilding the wall and that no gaps remained\u2014though
        we had not yet set up the doors in the gates. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Sanballat and Geshem sent a message asking me to meet them at
        one of the villages[COMMENT[0]] in the plain of Ono.\n\tBut I realized they
        were plotting to harm me, "
      comments:
      - number: '6:2 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek version; Hebrew reads '
          body: at Kephirim.
    - title: 
      content: "so I replied by sending this message to them: \u201CI am engaged
        in a great work, so I can\u2019t come. Why should I stop working to come
        and meet with you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Four times they sent the same message, and each time I gave the same
        reply. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The fifth time, Sanballat\u2019s servant came with an open letter
        in his hand, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and this is what it said:\n\t\u201CThere is a rumor among the surrounding
        nations, and Geshem[COMMENT[0]] tells me it is true, that you and the Jews
        are planning to rebel and that is why you are building the wall. According
        to his reports, you plan to be their king. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Gashmu, '
        - ft: a variant spelling of Geshem.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "He also reports that you have appointed prophets in Jerusalem to
        proclaim about you, \u2018Look! There is a king in Judah!\u2019\n\t\u201CYou
        can be very sure that this report will get back to the king, so I suggest
        that you come and talk it over with me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I replied, \u201CThere is no truth in any part of your story. You
        are making up the whole thing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They were just trying to intimidate us, imagining that they could
        discourage us and stop the work. So I continued the work with even greater
        determination.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:9 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'As in Greek version; Hebrew reads '
          body: But now to strengthen my hands.
    - title: 
      content: "Later I went to visit Shemaiah son of Delaiah and grandson of Mehetabel,
        who was confined to his home. He said, \u201CLet us meet together inside
        the Temple of God and bolt the doors shut. Your enemies are coming to kill
        you tonight.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I replied, \u201CShould someone in my position run from danger?
        Should someone in my position enter the Temple to save his life? No, I won\u2019t
        do it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I realized that God had not spoken to him, but that he had uttered
        this prophecy against me because Tobiah and Sanballat had hired him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They were hoping to intimidate me and make me sin. Then they would
        be able to accuse and discredit me.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember, O my God, all the evil things that Tobiah and Sanballat
        have done. And remember Noadiah the prophet and all the prophets like her
        who have tried to intimidate me.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Builders Complete the Wall
      content: "So on October 2[COMMENT[0]] the wall was finished\u2014just fifty-two
        days after we had begun. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:15 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'on the twenty-fifth day of the month Elul, '
        - ft: 'of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was October 2, 445 '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'When our enemies and the surrounding nations heard about it, they
        were frightened and humiliated. They realized this work had been done with
        the help of our God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During those fifty-two days, many letters went back and forth between
        Tobiah and the nobles of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For many in Judah had sworn allegiance to him because his father-in-law
        was Shecaniah son of Arah, and his son Jehohanan was married to the daughter
        of Meshullam son of Berekiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They kept telling me about Tobiah\u2019s good deeds, and then they
        told him everything I said. And Tobiah kept sending threatening letters to
        intimidate me."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: 'After the wall was finished and I had set up the doors in the gates,
        the gatekeepers, singers, and Levites were appointed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I gave the responsibility of governing Jerusalem to my brother Hanani,
        along with Hananiah, the commander of the fortress, for he was a faithful
        man who feared God more than most. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I said to them, \u201CDo not leave the gates open during the hottest
        part of the day.[COMMENT[0]] And even while the gatekeepers are on duty,
        have them shut and bar the doors. Appoint the residents of Jerusalem to act
        as guards, everyone on a regular watch. Some will serve at sentry posts and
        some in front of their own homes.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:3 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Keep the gates of Jerusalem closed until the sun is hot.
    - title: Nehemiah Registers the People
      content: 'At that time the city was large and spacious, but the population
        was small, and none of the houses had been rebuilt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So my God gave me the idea to call together all the nobles and leaders
        of the city, along with the ordinary citizens, for registration. I had found
        the genealogical record of those who had first returned to Judah. This is
        what was written there:  '
      comments: []
