            Ezra 3:9 and the note there.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "This included Mattaniah, Bakbukiah, and Obadiah.\n\tMeshullam, Talmon,
        and Akkub were the gatekeepers in charge of the storerooms at the gates. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These all served in the days of Joiakim son of Jeshua, son of Jehozadak,[COMMENT[0]]
        and in the days of Nehemiah the governor and of Ezra the priest and scribe.  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:26 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Jozadak, '
        - ft: a variant spelling of Jehozadak.
          body: 
    - title: "Dedication of Jerusalem\u2019s Wall"
      content: 'For the dedication of the new wall of Jerusalem, the Levites throughout
        the land were asked to come to Jerusalem to assist in the ceremonies. They
        were to take part in the joyous occasion with their songs of thanksgiving
        and with the music of cymbals, harps, and lyres. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The singers were brought together from the region around Jerusalem
        and from the villages of the Netophathites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also came from Beth-gilgal and the rural areas near Geba and
        Azmaveth, for the singers had built their own settlements around Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The priests and Levites first purified themselves; then they purified
        the people, the gates, and the wall.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I led the leaders of Judah to the top of the wall and organized two
        large choirs to give thanks. One of the choirs proceeded southward[COMMENT[0]]
        along the top of the wall to the Dung Gate. '
      comments:
      - number: '12:31 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: to the right.
    - title: 
      content: 'Hoshaiah and half the leaders of Judah followed them, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'along with Azariah, Ezra, Meshullam, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Judah, Benjamin, Shemaiah, and Jeremiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then came some priests who played trumpets, including Zechariah son
        of Jonathan, son of Shemaiah, son of Mattaniah, son of Micaiah, son of Zaccur,
        a descendant of Asaph. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Zechariah\u2019s colleagues were Shemaiah, Azarel, Milalai, Gilalai,
        Maai, Nethanel, Judah, and Hanani. They used the musical instruments prescribed
        by David, the man of God. Ezra the scribe led this procession. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At the Fountain Gate they went straight up the steps on the ascent
        of the city wall toward the City of David. They passed the house of David
        and then proceeded to the Water Gate on the east.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The second choir giving thanks went northward[COMMENT[0]] around
        the other way to meet them. I followed them, together with the other half
        of the people, along the top of the wall past the Tower of the Ovens to the
        Broad Wall, '
      comments:
      - number: '12:38 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: to the left.
    - title: 
      content: 'then past the Ephraim Gate to the Old City Gate,[COMMENT[0]] past
        the Fish Gate and the Tower of Hananel, and on to the Tower of the Hundred.
        Then we continued on to the Sheep Gate and stopped at the Guard Gate.  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:39 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'the Mishneh Gate, '
        - ft: 'or '
          body: the Jeshanah Gate.
    - title: 
      content: 'The two choirs that were giving thanks then proceeded to the Temple
        of God, where they took their places. So did I, together with the group of
        leaders who were with me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We went together with the trumpet-playing priests\u2014Eliakim, Maaseiah,
        Miniamin, Micaiah, Elioenai, Zechariah, and Hananiah\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and the singers\u2014Maaseiah, Shemaiah, Eleazar, Uzzi, Jehohanan,
        Malkijah, Elam, and Ezer. They played and sang loudly under the direction
        of Jezrahiah the choir director.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Many sacrifices were offered on that joyous day, for God had given
        the people cause for great joy. The women and children also participated
        in the celebration, and the joy of the people of Jerusalem could be heard
        far away.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Provisions for Temple Worship
      content: 'On that day men were appointed to be in charge of the storerooms
        for the offerings, the first part of the harvest, and the tithes. They were
        responsible to collect from the fields outside the towns the portions required
        by the Law for the priests and Levites. For all the people of Judah took
        joy in the priests and Levites and their work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They performed the service of their God and the service of purification,
        as commanded by David and his son Solomon, and so did the singers and the
        gatekeepers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The custom of having choir directors to lead the choirs in hymns
        of praise and thanksgiving to God began long ago in the days of David and
        Asaph. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: So now, in the days of Zerubbabel and of Nehemiah, all Israel brought
        a daily supply of food for the singers, the gatekeepers, and the Levites.
        The Levites, in turn, gave a portion of what they received to the priests,
        the descendants of Aaron.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Nehemiah\u2019s Various Reforms"
      content: 'On that same day, as the Book of Moses was being read to the people,
        the passage was found that said no Ammonite or Moabite should ever be permitted
        to enter the assembly of God.[COMMENT[0]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:1 '
        contents:
        - ft: See Deut 23:3-6.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'For they had not provided the Israelites with food and water in the
        wilderness. Instead, they hired Balaam to curse them, though our God turned
        the curse into a blessing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When this passage of the Law was read, all those of foreign descent
        were immediately excluded from the assembly.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Before this had happened, Eliashib the priest, who had been appointed
        as supervisor of the storerooms of the Temple of our God and who was also
        a relative of Tobiah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "had converted a large storage room and placed it at Tobiah\u2019s
        disposal. The room had previously been used for storing the grain offerings,
        the frankincense, various articles for the Temple, and the tithes of grain,
        new wine, and olive oil (which were prescribed for the Levites, the singers,
        and the gatekeepers), as well as the offerings for the priests.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I was not in Jerusalem at that time, for I had returned to King Artaxerxes
        of Babylon in the thirty-second year of his reign,[COMMENT[0]] though I later
        asked his permission to return. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'King Artaxerxes of Persia is here identified as the king of Babylon
            because Persia had conquered the Babylonian Empire. The thirty-second
            year of Artaxerxes was 433 '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "When I arrived back in Jerusalem, I learned about Eliashib\u2019s
        evil deed in providing Tobiah with a room in the courtyards of the Temple
        of God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I became very upset and threw all of Tobiah\u2019s belongings out
        of the room. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I demanded that the rooms be purified, and I brought back the
        articles for God\u2019s Temple, the grain offerings, and the frankincense.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I also discovered that the Levites had not been given their prescribed
        portions of food, so they and the singers who were to conduct the worship
        services had all returned to work their fields. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I immediately confronted the leaders and demanded, \u201CWhy has
        the Temple of God been neglected?\u201D Then I called all the Levites back
        again and restored them to their proper duties. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And once more all the people of Judah began bringing their tithes
        of grain, new wine, and olive oil to the Temple storerooms.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I assigned supervisors for the storerooms: Shelemiah the priest,
        Zadok the scribe, and Pedaiah, one of the Levites. And I appointed Hanan
        son of Zaccur and grandson of Mattaniah as their assistant. These men had
        an excellent reputation, and it was their job to make honest distributions
        to their fellow Levites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember this good deed, O my God, and do not forget all that I have
        faithfully done for the Temple of my God and its services.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In those days I saw men of Judah treading out their winepresses on
        the Sabbath. They were also bringing in grain, loading it on donkeys, and
        bringing their wine, grapes, figs, and all sorts of produce to Jerusalem
        to sell on the Sabbath. So I rebuked them for selling their produce on that
        day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some men from Tyre, who lived in Jerusalem, were bringing in fish
        and all kinds of merchandise. They were selling it on the Sabbath to the
        people of Judah\u2014and in Jerusalem at that!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I confronted the nobles of Judah. \u201CWhy are you profaning
        the Sabbath in this evil way?\u201D I asked. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWasn\u2019t it just this sort of thing that your ancestors
        did that caused our God to bring all this trouble upon us and our city? Now
        you are bringing even more wrath upon Israel by permitting the Sabbath to
        be desecrated in this way!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then I commanded that the gates of Jerusalem should be shut as darkness
        fell every Friday evening,[COMMENT[0]] not to be opened until the Sabbath
        ended. I sent some of my own servants to guard the gates so that no merchandise
        could be brought in on the Sabbath day. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:19 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: on the day before the Sabbath.
    - title: 
      content: 'The merchants and tradesmen with a variety of wares camped outside
        Jerusalem once or twice. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I spoke sharply to them and said, \u201CWhat are you doing out
        here, camping around the wall? If you do this again, I will arrest you!\u201D
        And that was the last time they came on the Sabbath. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I commanded the Levites to purify themselves and to guard the
        gates in order to preserve the holiness of the Sabbath.\n\tRemember this
        good deed also, O my God! Have compassion on me according to your great and
        unfailing love.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'About the same time I realized that some of the men of Judah had
        married women from Ashdod, Ammon, and Moab. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Furthermore, half their children spoke the language of Ashdod or
        of some other people and could not speak the language of Judah at all. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I confronted them and called down curses on them. I beat some
        of them and pulled out their hair. I made them swear in the name of God that
        they would not let their children intermarry with the pagan people of the
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWasn\u2019t this exactly what led King Solomon of Israel into
        sin?\u201D I demanded. \u201CThere was no king from any nation who could
        compare to him, and God loved him and made him king over all Israel. But
        even he was led into sin by his foreign wives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "How could you even think of committing this sinful deed and acting
        unfaithfully toward God by marrying foreign women?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One of the sons of Joiada son of Eliashib the high priest had married
        a daughter of Sanballat the Horonite, so I banished him from my presence.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Remember them, O my God, for they have defiled the priesthood and
        the solemn vows of the priests and Levites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So I purged out everything foreign and assigned tasks to the priests
        and Levites, making certain that each knew his work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I also made sure that the supply of wood for the altar and the first
        portions of the harvest were brought at the proper times.\n\tRemember this
        in my favor, O my God."
      comments: []
